<TEXT>
when political times were bad and his photograph 
album meant certain persecution li dachen buried it in the park 
near his house now he displays with pride the pictures of his 
days as a chinese student in leningrad 
this one is an old woman who lived near my dormitory he 
said cradling a torn photograph of a woman in a flowered apron 
she often cooked me lunch on the weekend but she is dead now i 
learned that from a letter a few years back 
li 65 is one of the thousands of chinese who studied in the 
soviet union during the 1950s before the two countries split in 
1960 over ideological and personal matters between their leaders 
the rift sent many chinese back home and left thousands more 
with friends and colleagues across the border wondering whether 
they would see them again 
in recent years however the two socialist giants have begun to 
heal that rift mikhail s gorbachev will come to china on monday 
in the first visit by a soviet leader to china in 30 years 
xing shugang one of chinas experts on the soviet union laughs 
when he thinks of his recent research 
it was like a great big joke the 59yearold professor said 
in an interview here i am a wellknown scholar and i had to talk 
to americans and japanese and australians about the soviet union 
finally i can go back 
xing who was president of the chinese students association in 
moscow from 1956 to 1959 met his first russian in 1947 when he 
went to harbin in northeastern china to learn the language 
we were the young cadres of the communist party i was 18 and 
ready to work for the motherland china and the soviet union were 
close allies then and we needed help in our war against chiang 
kaishek 
at the time harbin was home to hundreds of russians who had 
fled their homeland following the bolshevik revolution 
most of them didnt really hate the soviet government some 
were just afraid we were very close with them they were not just 
our teachers but our friends 
when the group returned to the soviet union in 1955 xing said 
he felt a great loss other soviets soon replaced them 
this was a different breed they were the experts he said 
referring to the thousands of soviet engineers scientists and 
businessmen who came to china in the 1950s to help develop the new 
communist country 
many were chauvinists always ordering the chinese about 
telling us what to do we chinese are proud people and dont take 
kindly to that kind of treatment 
when xing went to the soviet union in 1956 he looked up his old 
teachers from harbin 
i found olga kalenin a wonderful teacher in a small town 
outside moscow but it was very sad the soviet government had not 
been good to her they didnt treat her like one of their own her 
son had been forced to drive a truck others were washing dishes 
life as a student also had its unpleasant surprises 
we were closely watched by the kgb they were always trying to 
get information from us he said its an indication of the 
problems in both our governments that this fear was and is almost 
unshakeable 
even now xing said he sees great impediments between the two 
peoples 
both of our countries are changing rapidly but were not at 
the point where we can travel freely with no worries thats a 
question of human rights i hope that changes 
in his apartment with his photo album spread out on his bed li 
sighs and turns a page 
one way or the other this summit wont change my life the 
soviet union was my past now i have nothing to do with it 
a retired naval officer li studied engineering in leningrad in 
the 1950s during the ultraleftist cultural revolution of 196676 
he was suspected of being involved in a great spy ring of soviet 
agents 
it was then that i buried the book he said many of my 
old classmates burned theirs but i kept mine those were good 
years 
li said he remembers the first day he went to the hermitage in 
leningrad 
it was in late april it was a clear day and i was with my 
russian friends we spent the day looking at the beautiful 
paintings and listening to them recite pushkin then we drank 
vodka 
the album with its tattered cover is a sad book for li 
the friends and teachers i tried to keep in touch with have 
all died or left the country he said its been so long 
</TEXT>
