<TEXT>
max gordon who for 54 years operated the 
village vanguard one of the citys most influential jazz clubs 
and helped judy holliday and woody allen early in their careers 
has died he was 86 
gordon died thursday at st vincents hospital 
gordon ran the village vanguard in greenwich village and in 1942 
opened the blue angel in midtown manhattan the two clubs played an 
important part in the development and discovery of new talent 
friends said gordon had a talent for spotting new artists for 
his club such as holliday betty comden and adolph green 
other artists he helped early in their careers included barbra 
striesand pearl bailey dick gregory lenny bruce woody guthrie 
and leadbelly 
several artists such as john coltrane sonny rollins and joe 
henderson recorded at the village vanguard taking advantage of the 
clubs acoustics 
asked why he stayed in the business so long gordon once told an 
interviewer its my life its what i do 
gordon was born in svir lithuania and immigrated to the united 
states with his family at age 5 they moved to portland ore 
after graduating from reed college in 1924 he enrolled in 
columbia law school but after six weeks changed his mind and left 
the school 
he worked odd jobs for six years before a friend persuaded him 
to open a coffeehouse in greenwich village which he called the 
village fair two years later he opened the first village vanguard 
on greenwich avenue 
a year later he moved the vanguard to its present location at 
178 seventh ave south 
gordon is survived by his wife lorraine daughters rebecca and 
deborah and a sister sadye milich 
</TEXT>
