<TEXT>
congressional budget writers say they expect 
the house and senate to give final approval next week to a 117 
trillion spending plan for 1990 that claims a big deficit bite but 
leaves most federal priorities unmolested 
housesenate negotiators agreed to the plan which claims a 
997 billion deficit reduction by a unanimous voice vote 
thursday after only two short days of public meetings the few 
disagreements the two chambers had were worked out behind closed 
doors 
i dont expect any problems senate budget committee 
chairman jim sasser dtenn said when asked about the prospects 
for approval on the floor of congress 
democratic and republican leaders have been working together 
since the bush administration and congressional leaders forged a 
deal last month that settled most questions about spending levels 
and how to achieve savings on may 4 bipartisan majorities in the 
house and senate approved their own spending plans which differed 
little from each other 
in reaching their compromise the house agreed to the senates 
higher spending totals for energy and commerce programs while the 
two chambers compromised on education health law enforcement and 
community development initiatives 
one of the last disputes was resolved when the senate agreed to 
drop a provision that would have guaranteed 11 billion for public 
housing subsidies the decision will instead be left to congress 
appropriations committees which normally make most spending 
choices 
middle ground was also found in the 28 billion the package 
claims in deficit reduction for next year the senate agreed to 
reduce the 27 billion in savings it sought from the medicare 
program to 23 billion an amount expected to come from lowered 
payments to doctors and hospitals 
the makeup of 53 billion in additional tax receipts still must 
be determined a choice that is expected to be difficult president 
bush says 48 billion of it can come from cutting the capital 
gains tax but democrats say the plan is a handout to the wealthy 
and a moneyloser 
other fights are expected to be waged over a controversial 
proposal to raise 250 million by having the government sell 
broadcast rights and 400 million by licensing the production of 
chloroflourocarbons the chemicals blamed for depleting the earths 
ozone layer 
battles will also be raised over about 35 billion worth of 
undetermined savings expected to come from agriculture 
transportation community development health and other programs 
in addition out of 163 billion worth of savings that will 
require changes in the law the budget assigns only about half to 
specified congressional committees for action the budget simply 
assumes that the rest of the savings will occur an assumption that 
sen pete domenici of new mexico ranking republican on the senate 
budget committee said causes a very serious credibility 
problem 
the spending plan allows 2992 billion in defense spending 
42 billion less than the amount needed to keep up with inflation 
another 17 billion would be spent on foreign aid both totals were 
set in last months budget pact between bush and congress 
the budget has been savaged by critics who say it relies too 
heavily on unrealistic economic assumptions that make the deficit 
seem smaller and accounting gimmicks that create little real saving 
the lawmakers claim 850 million in savings by moving some 
payments for farmers from 1990 to this year and 200 million in 
