<DOCNO> AP890512-0054 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president bushs decision to order more us 
troops into panama and evacuate some american dependents in the 
wake of aborted elections and the beating of opposition leaders is 
another benchmark in the twoyear slide in relations between the 
two nations 
twentyfive years ago the united states and panama actually 
broke off diplomatic ties temporarily following antiamerican 
riots but the more recent government of gen manuel antonio 
noriega himself charged in the united states with drug 
trafficking has caused even more frustration and anger in 
washington 
here is a chronology of key events related to the noriega regime 
june 1987 col roberto diaz herrera the retiring 
secondincommand of the defense forces accuses noriega of 
drugrelated activities of rigging the 1984 election in favor of 
government candidates and of murdering dr hugo spadafora a 
former vice minister of health who had accused noriega of drug 
trafficking 
june 9 1987 a protest movement headed by the national civic 
crusade a grouping of professionals and students demands a probe 
into herreras allegations and a return to democracy street 
protests are crushed brutally 
feb 4 1988 a federal grand jury in miami indicts noriega on 
drug running charges a grand jury in tampa returns similar 
indictments 
feb 25 1988 president eric delvalle who was put in place by 
noriega announces he has fired his patron eight hours later the 
national assembly meets ousts delvalle and names manuel solis 
palma as minister in charge of the presidency a title he retains 
the united states refuses to recognize solis palma the government 
closes opposition news media 
march 16 1988 a coup organized by defense forces officers 
against noriega fails demonstrations erupt in the capital and a 
power outage blacks out the nation 
march 28 1988 after a large antinoriega march members of 
the defense forces enter the marriott hotel beating and arresting 
journalists and opposition leaders 
april 9 1988 the united states announces economic sanctions 
that prohibit american companies and the government from making 
payments to the panamanian government some 56 million in 
panamanian funds in american banks are frozen the united states 
tries to negotiate the departure of noriega without success 
may 9 1988 banks reopen but with severe restrictions 
including a freeze on savings accounts 
aug 21 1988 the united states charges there were more than 
240 cases of harassment of american military personnel by 
panamanian authorities so far that year 
sept 13 1988 the us defense department reduces the tour of 
duty for soldiers stationed in panama to lower the number of 
dependents in the country 
oct 30 1988 assistant secretary of state for interamerican 
affairs elliott abrams admits the reagan administrations efforts 
to oust noriega have failed 
april 9 1989 economic sanctions are renewed for one year on 
the basis that washington considers panama a threat to american 
security 
april and may 1989 the united states accuses panama of 
planning to win may 7 presidential elections by fraud news reports 
contend the united states authorized 10 million for the panamanian 
opposition which becomes a major campaign issue 
may 79 1989 the elections are held but noriegas victory 
claim is countered by rioters as well as international observers 
who say the ballots were rigged former president carter one of 
the us observers storms out of panamas vote tabulation center 
and denounces noriega as a dictator who was stealing the election 
the protest is echoed in congress and at the white house which 
says independent exit polling showed noriegas slate was losing by 
a 3to1 margin one senator introduces legislation calling for 
abrogation of the panama canal treaties but the white house 
rejects that approach 
may 10 1989 as defense forces look on thugs loyal to noriega 
beat opposition candidate guillermo endara and his two running 
mates and one of their bodyguards is killed the 
noriegacontrolled electoral tribunal declares the elections null 
and void in their totality but we won and we will continue 
to fight says guillermo ford the bloodied second vice 
presidential candidate 
may 11 1989 president bush orders 2000 additional us 
military troops to panama joining 10000 already there and decides 
to evacuate more of the american dependents there some of the 
dependents will be sent home others moved to military bases for 
safety 
</TEXT>
