<DOCNO> AP890512-0056 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
us health officials are urging testing 
isolation and other measures to curb the spread of tuberculosis in 
the nations prisons 
centers for disease control researchers cited a survey in 29 
states where prisons reported 31 tuberculosis cases per 100000 
inmates in 198485 compared with eight cases per 100000 among 
nonincarcerated adults in those states during the same period 
in some large correctional systems the incidence of tb has 
increased dramatically the cdc said in its report thursday 
it noted especially high rates in new york new jersey and 
california 
tuberculosis a contagious bacterial lung disease infects 
about 22000 people each year in the united states most can be 
cured with drug treatment scientists estimate that about 10 
million americans are infected with the virus but the vast 
majority will never get the disease 
the spread of aidsvirus infections during this decade may play 
a part in the spread of tb in prisons the atlantabased cdc said 
aids weakens the immune systems of patients making them more 
susceptible to infections which other people might fight off 
including tuberculosis 
tests for acquired immune deficiency syndrome should be offered 
to all inmates with known tb infections the cdc report said 
persons at highest risk are close contacts the cdc 
said noting that tb can pose particular problems in prisons 
where the environment is often conducive to airborne transmission 
of infection among inmates staff and visitors 
the cdc committee recommends new tests at least once a year 
rapid chest xrays for tbinfected people showing symptoms and 
isolation for those with suspected or confirmed symptomatic tb 
cases 
isolation should include separate ventilation systems to cut 
down the risk of airborne transmission of tb the committee said 
it may be necessary to move a patient to another facility or 
hospital with a respiratory isolation facility the panel said 
prison overcrowding may be a cause for spreading tb said dr 
dixie snider a cdc tuberculosis specialist 
in new york there were 106 tb cases per 100000 inmates in 1986 
seven times more than the average of 15 cases reported in 197678 
inmates in new jersey had a tb rate of 110 per 100000 in 1987 
11 times higher than the general new jersey population in 
california the 80 per 100000 rate was nearly six times higher 
than in the general population 
