<TEXT>
more than 200 people were out of their 
homes today after a midsouth railroad train derailed and spilled 
thousands of gallons of antifreeze and diesel fuel into the chunky 
river authorities said 
no injuries were reported in the derailment which occurred 
about 830 pm thursday 10 miles west of here but officials said 
the chemicals and diesel fuel that leaked near and into the river 
created a pollution hazard booms were placed downriver from the 
spill site to catch leaking fuel 
the evacuees who included 22 nursing home patients and about 
200 other people may have to stay away from their homes until 
sunday authorities said 
we now estimate that 20000 to 25000 gallons of ethylene 
glycol alcohol antifreeze got into the river along with 3000 
to 5000 gallons of diesel fuel said eleana turner spokeswoman 
for the mississippi bureau of pollution control 
investigators did not know what caused the derailment which 
involved 12 cars and three engines two of the engines fell into 
the river which runs parallel to the railroad tracks 
we have directed a precautionary evacuation in a onemile 
radius around the derailment site said jim maher director of 
the mississippi emergency management agency 
six of the derailed cars carried the ethylene glycol alcohol or 
antifreeze at least three leaked but it was believed that only 
one of the three spilled a significant amount of the chemical said 
dusty perkins a spokesman for the mississippi emergency management 
agency 
authorities told people downstream from the derailment to stay 
away from the river and keep livestock away from it because 
drinking high concentrations of antifreeze can be fatal the booms 
set up to contain the diesel fuel would not stop the antifreeze 
perkins said but the water would eventually dilute it 
our concern now is a pollution concern rather than a public 
safety concern perkins said nobody is going to breathe any 
toxic fumes from this and die but we dont know what will happen 
to the river 
a car containing about 20000 gallons of sodium hydroxide a 
powder also called caustic soda that is used in a variety of 
industries spilled right next to the river 
perkins said first reports indicated some of the caustic soda 
had entered the river but we have a correction from the scene 
that it has been contained and did not get into the chunky 
sandy metrolis of the lauderdale county emergency management 
agency said some people on the scene complained of burning eyes and 
a strong odor but as far as the effect on the river i dont 
know she said 
four derailed cars carried vinyl chloride but they werent 
leaking while the 12th derailed car had plastic beads that would 
be hazardous only if burned 
perkins said that the federal environmental protection agency 
was bringing in sampling equipment to determine the spills effect 
on the river 
lauderdale county deputy david taylor said a community center in 
meridien was set up as a shelter for the 200 people who live within 
a mile of the derailment site 
 
