workers compensation benefits awarded 
to a flight attendent who broke a leg while skiing during a layover 
in oregon have been reversed by a state appeals court 
the 1st district court of appeals previously has allowed 
benefits for injuries sustained off duty while on 
employmentrelated trips but it ruled the skiing trip didnt count 
we cannot conclude in the instant case that a 58mile daytrip 
to pursue ones love of skiing is either a minimal deviation or a 
reasonable and foreseeable activity especially in light of the 
nature of the sport of skiing which involves a great amount of 
risk district judge j klein wigginton wrote in the wednesday 
opinion 
a threejudge panel unanimously reversed benefits that had been 
awarded to eastern airlines flight attendant chandler rigdon by a 
state deputy commissioner of workers compensation the award was 
appealed by eastern and north river insurance co 
wigginton wrote that the skiing accident differed from an injury 
suffered by another eastern employee in a basketball game played at 
a ymca gym for which benefits were allowed by the court in a 1985 
case 
he noted guests at the hotel where the employee was staying had 
gym visitation rights and the game constituted sports activity 
reasonably necessary for personal health and recreation just like 
swimming in the hotel pool 
in a 1986 case the appeal court also allowed benefits for a pan 
am employee injured when a matchbook went up in flames as she was 
lighting a cigarette ruling that smoking is related to personal 
comfort 
we cannot conceive of a rule that would include downhill 
skiing in a list of such personal activities as drinking 
breathing eating or even smoking wigginton wrote 
the court also has allowed compensation for offduty injuries in 
activities that increase productivity as in the case of a lawn 
maintenance employee who was hurt when he took a dip in a river 
during a break 
