<TEXT>
the father of an 11yearold girl was irate when a 
drugstore chain sent him a letter demanding he fork over 100 
because his daughter allegedly swiped an 89cent tube of lip balm 
he was successful in fighting the demand but retailers across 
the country are increasingly dispatching similar missives to 
shoplifters and their parents newly armed with state laws giving 
stores more power to fight sticky fingers 
the reason its popular it acts as a deterrent when the word 
gets out when you steal from the store youre going to pay for 
it carol sommer a founder of civil demand associates in sherman 
oaks calif said in an interview friday the 4yearold firm has 
clients nationwide and is only one of several law firms dedicated 
to this new weapon against shoplifting 
the tactic of recouping shoplifting losses by sending demand 
letters to shoplifters or their parents is known in the business as 
civil recovery or civil restitution 
its a boon for getting some money back said jack fraser 
operations chief for the new yorkbased national retail merchants 
association which has 55000 member stores 
according to fbi figures gathered from police nationwide for 
1987 the latest numbers available there 11 million shoplifting 
offenses averaging 96 per item 
since nevada passed the countrys first law offering retailers a 
civil remedy in 1973 it has been joined by 34 others the law 
takes various forms but the message is the same shoplifters wont 
get away with just a red face they can be hounded until they pay 
up 
laws governing civil recovery vary widely from state to state 
but in all of them adult shoplifters are held liable for damages 
and penalties in about half the states stores can go after minors 
by making parents responsible for restitution according to delany 
stinson senior investigations coordinator at dayton hudson 
department store co in minneapolis 
some states require that police be notified others like 
massachusetts do not 
some states restrict repayment to the value of the item others 
allow the retailer to tote up the additional costs of crime 
prevention damage to displays or injuries that occurred when the 
shoplifter was nabbed and even the cost of putting a new price tag 
on the stolen merchandise ms stinson said 
mrs sommer of civil demand associates stressed that demand 
letters are not intended to generate profits 
this is not a moneymaking operation mrs sommer said 
its meant to be a deterrent thats really the bottom line 
each time somebody gets in trouble at least 20 people know 
about it the word does get into the community said lewis 
shealy head of loss prevention at marshall fields and co 
department stores for five years the store has been demanding 300 
from each shoplifter last year it recouped close to 100000 
thats paying the salary of at least six security guards 
shealy said from his chicago headquarters which spends about 5 
million a year on guards and antitheft devices 
the success rate varies from 25 percent recovery to up to 90 
percent loss prevention experts say the betterheeled the 
shoplifter the easier it is to collect restitution largely 
because they are easier to track down than more transient lower 
income earners 
the massachusetts case of the girl and the lip balm was an 
instance of the retailer the cvs drugstore chain going further 
than the law allows the state attorney general said 
massachusetts law says parents of youngsters 7 to 17 years old 
are only liable for the cost of the item adult shoplifters can be 
taken to small claims court where they may be ordered to pay 50 
to 500 in damages on top of the items cost 
 
