a school official friday defended a jobtraining 
program that teaches housekeeping to developmentally disabled 
students but admitted he erred by letting students clean the homes 
of teachers and principals 
the madison school of the wyandotte district has 183 
developmentally disabled students from 14 detroitarea school 
districts the students are sent to a number of sites for job 
training and superintendent michael williamson said housekeeping 
is part of the training 
the program provides an excellent opportunity for handicapped 
youngsters and can afford them some measure of independence 
williamson said 
i think there was an error in judgment made in using teachers 
and principals homes because it leaves us open to 
exploitation by the public and the press 
on wednesday the mothers of two of the students sandra adkins 
and laura murphy filed suit in wayne county circuit court 
claiming they never gave permission for their disabled children to 
be used in child slavery 
williamson said the lawsuit was outrageous exploitation on the 
part of the mothers 
the lawsuit asks the court to end housekeeping training unless 
the students receive parental permission and are paid minimum wage 
the women allege their daughters had to clean and scrub floors at 
the homes of teachers and principals 
they are supposed to be learning for future employability 
said richard a neaton the mothers lawyer i seriously question 
whether they need to clean teachers homes to do that 
adkins and murphy said they had given permission only for their 
children to receive training in a clothing store 
when the parents told us they didnt want their kids to go we 
honored those parents requests madison principal cheri kodrich 
said the lawsuit came as a total shock i have nothing to 
defend what we do is legitimate 
williamson and kodrich said all parents were notified in writing 
that their children might work at different sites if another 
student missed school the mothers said they never received such 
notice 
