a cheyennearapaho woman disabled from polio 
said friday she cant get welfare as long as she is on federal oil 
royalty rolls and since those checks stopped coming regularly she 
lost her home and children 
mary limpy choked back tears as she told a special investigating 
committee of the senate select committee on indian affairs that she 
has lived three years in an abandoned house in oklahoma city 
because she could not pay her bills 
the checks stopped coming regularly in 1983 said mrs limpy 
who said the state took custody of her two youngest children two 
years ago 
now the money comes sporadically and the bureau of indian 
affairs which manages her three wells cant say why she told the 
committee 
i do not get my royalty checks right after the gas or oil is 
sold she said i get my checks sometimes four to seven months 
later recently it has been about four months later 
she said the checks average 30 to 60 she told the committee 
she would be better off if she did not have the royalties at all 
and could apply for state welfare 
mrs limpy said her wells originally were leased by the tenneco 
oil co which sold the leases to koch oil she said at one point 
she heard the wells had been capped but the farmer who works the 
land where the wells are located said trucks kept going on and off 
the oilfield 
witnesses before the committee earlier in the week testified 
that koch which is based in wichita kan had been stealing oil 
from indian wells a charge the company has denied 
mrs limpy is part of a federal classaction lawsuit charging 
that the government has violated its trust responsibilities to 
