<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency proposed 
friday to bar two missouri plants of a defense contractor from 
receiving any future federal funds because of alleged water 
pollution violations 
the epa said its move is part of a crackdown on industrial 
polluters it was the first time the agency has started an 
enforcement action under the clean water act to cut off federal 
funds to government contractors for allegedly failing to comply 
with pollution standards 
targeted were two joplin mo plants of eaglepicher industries 
inc an ohiobased company that makes batteries for defense 
aerospace and automotive industries 
the epa alleges that the plants have discharged untreated waste 
water into a creek and dumped toxic wastes including mercury 
cadmium and chromium into the citys sewer system in excess of 
federal limits 
the agency filed a lawsuit in federal court in missouri against 
the plants in october 1987 alleging the water pollution violations 
company officials in joplin and at the cincinnati ohio office 
of eaglepicher would not comment on epas proposed action or 
whether the company will seek a hearing to contest it 
if epa implements the sanction it would not invalidate existing 
government contracts of the two plants or halt the flow of money 
under them according to dave ryan an epa spokesman 
however those contracts could not be renewed and the two 
plants would be barred from receiving any future federal money 
