<TEXT>
a state appeals court friday called 
floridas abortionconsent law constitutionally infirm 
agreeing with a lower court judge who had declared the law could 
not be enforced 
in a 21 ruling the 5th district court of appeal here upheld a 
decision by lake circuit judge jerry lockett who ruled may 4 that 
the law requiring parental or judicial consent for a minor to seek 
an abortion was too vague 
the appeals court also said the state law failed to protect the 
privacy of minors guaranteed under roe v wade the 1973 us 
supreme court decision which made abortion legal 
the appeals court remanded the case back to lockett with the 
order than he dismiss the petition filed by a 15yearold pregnant 
teenager who had sought his permission for an abortion 
the decision to terminate the pregnancy is up to the girl 
and her physician without state regulation the court ruled 
the court said the vagueness of the law opened up a clear 
danger that trial judges would render a decision on the basis of 
their own moral religious or political beliefs regarding 
abortion 
the appellate courts rulings are binding statewide unless as 
often happens in controversial cases another state appeals court 
takes a similar case and reaches a different decision said volusia 
circuit judge c mcferrin smith 
then for the decision to apply statewide it would have to be 
appealed to the florida supreme court 
the law approved by the legislature last year requires single 
girls under 18 to get permission from a parent guardian or judge 
before obtaining an abortion 
the law says judges can approve an abortion if they decide the 
girl is sufficiently mature to make the decision if consent is 
unreasonably withheld by a parent or guardian or if the girl fears 
emotional or physical abuse if she tells her parents 
lockett declared the law unconstitutional after being asked to 
give permission for an abortion to a 15yearold girl who was 11 
weeks pregnant 
lockett said the law was too vague and couldnt be properly 
handled in the courts lockett in his ruling said he couldnt hold 
a proper hearing on the issue because hes unsure what the law 
means by sufficiently mature 
the florida law took effect oct 1 five days later a federal 
court barred its enforcement because no implementation rules were 
included the ban was lifted when the florida supreme court issued 
the rules in february 
the lake case was appealed by attorney jerry blair of leesburg 
who is representing the girl all of the proceedings are secret and 
court files are sealed to protect her identity 
</TEXT>
