<TEXT>
the alaska oil disaster is prompting congress 
to revisit an idea that has languished on capitol hill for 15 
years the creation of a governmentcontrolled fund to pay for an 
oil spills devastation 
the bush administration on thursday sent to a house panel a 
proposal for a 500 million emergency fund to deal with oil spill 
cleanup and recovery the money would come from a 13centabarrel 
fee on all domestic and imported petroleum 
as transportation secretary samuel skinner explained the details 
to members of the subcommittee on coast guard and navigation 
several panel members noted that the subject is far from new 
rep gerry studds dmass pointed out that similar legislation 
has been debated without attracting much interest in every congress 
since 1975 three times bills cleared the house but not the senate 
i hope were not going to reinvent the wheel weve had 
numerous hearings on this said rep donald young ralaska 
but the spill of 11 million gallons of oil from the exxon valdez 
tanker in alaskas prince william sound on march 24 and the 
problems that have surfaced since then in containing and cleaning 
up the oil have virtually ensured that similar legislation will 
pass this year some congressmen suggested 
it took a tragedy like the exxon valdez to cause the entire 
congress to focus on the issue said rep walter jones dokla 
chairman of the merchant marine and fisheries committee 
in addition to the administration bill the house is considering 
a slightly different measure sponsored by jones that calls for a 
300 million cleanup fund 
some provisions of the administration bill likely will be 
incorporated into jones bill one congressional staffer said a 
subcommittee vote already is scheduled for later this month 
the fund would be tapped only for costs beyond those for which 
the company or shipper is directly liable the administrations 
legislation establishes a 78 million liability ceiling while the 
jones bill sets a 60 million maximum 
legislation was introduced in the senate on wednesday by sen 
ted stevens ralaska calling for creation of a 500 million 
federal oil spill cleanup fund it too would be financed through 
a fee on domestic and imported oil 
the stevens legislation also would require the coast guard to 
respond to a major oil spill and would give the coast guard access 
to up to 150 million of the cleanup fund 
in more than a dozen congressional hearings since the exxon 
valdez spill congressmen have bemoaned the lack of industry and 
government preparedness to such an emergency 
skinner who has been the bush administrations point man on the 
alaska spill said when the exxon valdez ran aground the 
government had only a few million dollars available in oil spill 
recovery funds 
had that spill been caused by a company less welltodo than the 
exxon corp the government would have had to scramble for funds 
and ask congress for tens of millions of dollars to get the cleanup 
effort going skinner said 
estimates of the cost of the exxon spill the worst in us 
history ranged from about 100 million to many times that amount 
skinner said it was too early to predict the eventual total 
salaries for the thousands of workers cleaning the fouled alaska 
beaches alone run as high as 75000 an hour for 20hour work days 
skinner said 
the numbers are very big he continued indicating at one 
point that even the proposed 500 million cleanup fund might have 
been inadequate he suggested that something in the range of 500 
million to 1 billion should cover it 
the administration proposal would make 500 million available in 
the event of another major spill but skinner said the president 
would have the authority to exceed that amount the government 
could then seek additional fees from the industry 
