<TEXT>
in a journey that took them to the heart of 
capitalism a chinese delegation visited several us futures 
exchanges this week in hopes of creating socialiststyle 
commodity markets back home 
their signing today of an agreement with the chicago board of 
trade to establish a beijingbased training program for chinese 
traders is yet another sign of the chinese governments willingness 
to bend the communist line to accomodate useful freemarket 
concepts 
under the agreement cbot personnel will spend up to one month 
each year in the chinese capital to teach intensified courses on 
futures markets and trading techniques the cbot said the 
chinese will send economists to chicago for a workstudy program on 
the cbot floor 
we will adapt the futures market from the western style into 
socialist style a combination of the two systems said lu jian 
guang the only englishspeaking member of the fourman group 
and although professional speculators and highrisk futures 
contracts probably wont be part of the first chinese grain 
exchange theres no telling how far things could go once the 
bidding begins 
it all depends on the outside environment political reforms 
as well as economic reforms lu said thursday 
a chinese commodity market would be unique in the communist 
world said david granick a professor of economics at the 
university of wisconsin 
so far as i know ive never read of nor heard any talk of 
commmodity markets in any communist country he said 
the free market reigns supreme on the chicago board of trade 
the worlds oldest and largest commodity market where traders 
compete aggressively sometimes violently to buy and sell 
contracts for future deliveries of commodities ranging from 
soybeans to treasury bonds 
the new agreement expands a deal struck between the board of 
trade and the international trade research institute of chinas 
ministry of foreign economic relations and trade in april 1986 to 
exchange visitors with an eye toward developing some sort of 
commodities market in china 
the chinese initiated the exchange because they wanted to gain 
a fuller understanding of the nature and workings of futures 
markets said pat catania the board of trades marketing 
director 
catania said the chinese have tried futures trading in such 
commodities as corn sugar and tin in markets in chicago new york 
and london 
a futures market functions as an insurance policy for producers 
and consumers of agricultural commodities such as wheat or cattle 
it allows these commercial players to lock in prices in advance 
thus protecting themselves from price swings caused by weather 
problems plant disease or other disasters 
the board of trade began its life 140 years ago as a place for 
commercial grain players to both make deals and deliver goods but 
no one takes physical delivery of grain there any more 
most contracts are settled in cash a feature that invites 
professional speculators to play the markets and has earned the 
exchange and other futures markets a reputation as glorified 
casinos 
lu said chinas first grain exchange which probably will be 
located in the agricultural hunan province would hark back to the 
early days of the board of trade grain farmers and grain users 
would use the exchange to agree in advance on prices but 
individual speculators would be barred 
he would not predict a startup date for the first chinese 
commodity market 
the chinese who spent most of their weeklong us stay in 
chicago also visited the kansas city board of trade and the 
minneapolis grain exchange 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

