<TEXT>
the alar scare has already cost washington 
apple growers 90 million this year and slumping prices and sales 
reported friday indicate losses will be even higher 
sales dropped 15 percent last week while prices have slumped 
another 1 per box both attributed to continuing public concern 
over the possible health effects of the farm chemical 
the outlook is even gloomier because round two of the alar 
controversy is about to begin with more news reports a 
congressional hearing and movement by the us environmental 
protection agency toward banning the chemical 
bill dewitt of the wenatchee valley traffic association reported 
friday that outofstate shipments of washington apples were 12 
million 42pound boxes during the week that ended thursday 
that compared to nearly 15 million boxes the week before and 
nearly 17 million boxes the same week last year 
shipments to retailers are considered an accurate indicator of 
consumer sales 
tom hale president of the washington state apple commission 
has attributed the decline to retailers dropping their inventories 
until the impact of the latest alar battle becomes clear 
the industry is anxiously awaiting another alar report on the 
cbs television program 60 minutes scheduled for this sunday 
the shows story on the nrdc report in late february sparked the 
controversy 
the industry has contacted people interviewed for the second 
60 minutes story and believes it will be a negative piece 
its an attempt to offset the broad criticism the original 
segment had said hale who heads the promotion group for the 
states 5000 growers 
also set for next week are congressional hearings on food safety 
that will focus on alar and the epa announced thursday that it 
plans to begin formal steps to ban alar within 10 days 
the nrdc report concluded that eating apples treated with alar 
the trade name for daminozide increased cancer risk in children 
the industry has attacked the report as misleading and federal 
regulators have pronounced apples safe to eat but alarmed 
consumers have backed away 
alar is sprayed on apple trees in the spring and is used 
primarily to improve color and crispness and extend shelf life of 
red apples 
washington grows about half the nations apples but provides 88 
percent of the domestic production this time of year the states 
growers have been hardest hit by the controversy 
prices which were 13 to 14 per box just before the 
controversy erupted in late february have dropped to around 10 
per box in recent weeks said jeff main of the federalstate market 
news service in yakima 
with about 30 million boxes of red apples sold since late 
february the cost to washington growers about 90 million 
those losses are partially offset by increases in prices for 
much smaller supplies of golden delicious and granny smith apples 
warehouses in the state still have over 13 million boxes of red 
apples left in storage 3 million more than at this time last year 
if we dont sell all of these which is a possibility we will 
lose much more dewitt said 
earlier this week john rice president of the international 
apple institute estimated that the controversy had cost growers 
across the nation 100 million with another 100 million lost by 
juice and applesauce processors 
the sales slowdown also means that stored fruit which normally 
would have been sold a month ago is becoming unsuitable for 
supermarkets and must be diverted at a much lower price to juice 
and sauce makers 
</TEXT>
